			<p>For many Vancouver hosts planning weddings, corporate events, or family celebrations, the question of halal catering arrives with a lot of uncertainty. What does halal mean exactly? Does the entire menu need to be halal? How do I know a caterer is genuinely halal-certified versus just claiming to be? After fifteen years of catering across the Lower Mainland's diverse communities, we've answered these questions hundreds of times — here's what we wish every host knew.</p>

			<h2>What <em>Halal</em> Actually Means</h2>

			<p>Halal, in the context of food, means permissible under Islamic dietary law. For meat to be considered halal, the animal must be slaughtered following specific guidelines — invoking the name of Allah, swift slaughter using a sharp knife, full draining of blood, and the animal must be healthy and not have eaten any forbidden foods. Pork and alcohol are never halal.</p>

			<p>For Indian catering in particular, this matters most for chicken, lamb, and goat dishes. Vegetarian dishes are inherently halal as long as they don't contain alcohol or alcohol-derived ingredients. Most Indian vegetarian curries are naturally halal-friendly.</p>

			<h2>Halal Certification <em>vs. Halal Claims</em></h2>

			<p>Anyone can claim "we serve halal." Real halal certification is different — it means a caterer's meat suppliers are certified by recognised halal certification bodies, and there's documentation behind the claim. In Canada, look for suppliers certified by organisations like the Islamic Food and Nutrition Council of Canada (IFANCC) or comparable certification bodies.</p>

			<p>The right questions to ask:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Which halal certification body does your meat supplier use?</li>
				<li>Can you share documentation if requested?</li>
				<li>Is all your chicken and lamb halal by default, or only on request?</li>
				<li>How is halal meat stored and prepared separately from non-halal?</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Does the <em>Whole Menu</em> Need to Be Halal?</h2>

			<p>This is one of the most common questions we get. The answer depends on your guests.</p>

			<p>If you're hosting a wedding where some families observe halal strictly and others don't, you have a few options. The most respectful approach is to make the entire meat menu halal-certified — this way, every Muslim guest can eat anything on the table without checking. Pork and alcohol service can still be excluded entirely if needed for religious considerations.</p>

			<p>For corporate events and mixed gatherings, having clearly labelled halal options alongside other dishes works well. The key is clarity — guests shouldn't have to guess.</p>

			<h2>Beyond <em>the Meat</em></h2>

			<p>Strictly observant Muslim guests may also avoid:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Alcohol in cooking (some Indian dishes use wine reductions or vodka)</li>
				<li>Vanilla extract (often alcohol-based) — some bakers use halal vanilla alternatives</li>
				<li>Gelatin from non-halal sources (in some desserts)</li>
				<li>Cross-contamination — utensils, surfaces, or oils that have touched pork</li>
			</ul>

			<p>A caterer experienced in halal catering will already be thinking about these things. Asking explicitly about cross-contamination protocols is a good test of their experience.</p>

			<h2>How Sula Approaches <em>Halal Catering</em></h2>

			<p>All chicken and lamb dishes at Sula are prepared using halal-certified meat sourced from trusted local BC suppliers. We've been doing this since day one because Vancouver's catering community has always been multi-cultural, and because halal sourcing is a baseline expectation, not a special request.</p>

			<p>For weddings or events with strict observance requirements, we work with the host to ensure separate preparation, clearly labelled dishes, and thoughtful coordination across the menu. Vegetarian and vegan dishes are prepared in dedicated kitchen areas to support Jain and pure-vegetarian needs at the same event.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

			<p>Halal isn't an add-on — it's a baseline of respect for guests whose faith matters to them. The best caterers don't treat it as a checkbox; they build it into how they source, prepare, and serve food. If you're planning an event in Vancouver and need genuine halal Indian catering, ask the right questions, look for real certifications, and choose a caterer that's been doing this long enough to do it well.</p>

